sual powers of imaginative re-creation, Berlin brings to life original minds that swam against the current of their times--and still challenge conventional wisdom. In a new foreword to this corrected edition, which also includes a new appendix of letters in which Berlin discusses and further illuminates some of its topics, noted essayist Mark Lilla argues that Berlin's decision to give up a philosophy fellowship and become a historian of ideas represented not an abandonment of philosophy but a decision to do philosophy by other, perhaps better, means. "His instinct told him," Lilla writes, "that you learn more about an idea as an idea when you know something about its genesis and understand why certain people found it compelling and were spurred to action by it." This collection of fascinating intellectual portraits is a rich demonstration of that belief.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPhilosophie. 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aHardy, Henry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHausheer, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHausheer, Roger.1 aLilla, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLilla, Mark.1 aMatthews, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMill, J. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140084323740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400843237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400843237.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles